liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Daniel Andrews says the Labor caucus will meet at midday tomorrow and he won't speculate on who may be elected as his successor. "That'll be determined by the colleagues and I am deeply respectful of that process," he says.

children.content: Daniel Andrews says the Labor caucus will meet at midday tomorrow and he won't speculate on who may be elected as his successor.
"That'll be determined by the colleagues and I am deeply respectful of that process," he says.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: "You're all good?" begins Mr Andrews, before asking "you guys right to go?" in his trademark fashion. He says serving as premier has been the "honour and privilege of his life". He says he is proud of his government's legacy of "getting things done". "Today I will again visit Government House and resign as premier and member for Mulgrave, effective 5pm tomorrow," he says. "It's not an easy decision because as much as we've achieved together there's so much more to do. "But when it's time, it's time."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ANZ has been ordered by the Federal Court to to pay a $15 million penalty for misleading customers about funds available in certain credit card accounts. The Australian lender falsely indicated to customers that they could rely on a 'cash advance' from funds stated to be their 'Available Funds' without incurring fees and interest. The error resulted in customers being charged with thousands of dollars in fees while the average remediation paid was around $45 per affected account, according to the Australian Securities & Investments Commission (ASIC) — the regulator which sued ANZ. "Many ANZ customers relied on the account information displayed by the bank and were charged fees that were inconsistent with that information," said ASIC deputy chair Sarah Court. So far, the country's fourth-largest bank has provided remediation payments of more than $8.3 million to about 186,000 accounts that were charged with fees and interest between May 2016 and November 2018. "The court found ANZ breached the ASIC Act and the National Consumer Credit Protection Act," the regulator said. In a separate statement, the lender acknowledged the breach and agreed to further remediation for the period from November 2018 to September 2021. "ANZ accepts responsibility for what has occurred and apologises to its customers, and has addressed the issues that gave rise to the contraventions," the lender said.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ANZ fined $15m for misleading customers over funds

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Qantas shares are losing value as pressure mounts on the chairman Richard Goyder to step down. The airline has also warned higher fuel costs may push ticket prices up. Analyst firm Jefferies has lowered its earning per share (EPS) forecast for Qantas by 14 per cent, but says "positive" customer improvement initiatives along with ongoing strength in demand suggest damage to the brand is fixable. By 12:15pm AEST, Qantas' share price was down 1.5% t o $5.15. It looks even worse when you step back and look at Qantas shares. They have dropped 5.3% in the past week, and have plunged 17.3% in the past month.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hi everyone — Rachel Pupazzoni jumping in to say hi. The leader on the ASX today is medical imaging company Pro Medicus after securing a $140 million, 10-year contract with the largest not-for-profit healthcare system in Texas, Baylor Scott & White Health. Its shares jumped 9.3 per cent at the open, but have pared back a little to 9 per cent — to be valued at $77.62 a share, shortly after 11am AEST. Pro Medicus will supply cloud-engineered imaging services, starting in the first quarter of 2024. "Baylor Scott & White Health joins our impressive list of IDN and Tier 1 academic clients and represents our first major client in Texas." Dr Sam Hupert, the chief executive of Pro Medicus, told the market: "The scale and scope of our initiative with Baylor Scott & White Health is noteworthy and will include nearly 500 radiologists who will be exposed to the benefits of Visage 7."
